3523). We improved the upper bound to 𝐶4 ≤ 0.3521 with a similar linear\nHermite polynomials 𝐻4𝑘 ( 𝑥 ). This form is particularly useful because the Fourier transform of\n𝐻𝑛 ( 𝑥 ) 𝑒−𝜋𝑥 is 𝑖𝑛 𝐻𝑛 ( 𝜉) 𝑒−𝜋𝜉 . For an even polynomial 𝑃 ( 𝑥 ) = 𝑐4𝑘 𝐻4𝑘 ( 𝑥 ), the Fourier transform\n[ 𝑐0 , 𝑐1 , 𝑐2 ] ≈ [0.32925, −0.01159, −8.9216 × 10−5 ]. Using these coefficients to construct\n2 /(2𝜋) yields the improved upper bound 𝐶 ≤ 0.3521. Qualitatively our\n0.3284. By incorporating their refined approach into AlphaEvolve, we improved our reported\nconstant further to 0.3216. For details, we refer to the accompanying Google Colab.\n0.8","stderr":"","interrupted":false,"isImage":false,"noOutputExpected":false},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"0efce67f-5985-4020-a3ca-3180bd0ae41d","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main","slug":"bright-wondering-lantern"}
{"parentUuid":"ab6a5168-c116-4cb3-adfe-9cb9f2ed48f2","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"a2c2fb2f89230a0db","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-8","id":"msg_018vHHGXA2e1PrKYN8orRoVv","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"I have everything from the primary white paper, cross-checked against the DeepMind blog and IEEE Spectrum. Here are the findings.\n\n---\n\n## AlphaEvolve (Google DeepMind, 2025) — Concrete Results on Mathematics and Algorithms\n\nAll numbers below are verified against the **primary DeepMind white paper** (\"AlphaEvolve: A coding agent for scientific and algorithmic discovery\"), cross-checked against the DeepMind blog and IEEE Spectrum. The white paper is arXiv 2506.13131; the DeepMind-hosted PDF carries identical text.\n\n**Primary source URLs used:**\n- White paper PDF: `https://storage.googleapis.com/deepmind-media/DeepMind.com/Blog/alphaevolve-a-gemini-powered-coding-agent-for-designing-advanced-algorithms/AlphaEvolve.pdf`\n- DeepMind blog: `https://deepmind.google/discover/blog/alphaevolve-a-gemini-powered-coding-agent-for-designing-advanced-algorithms/`\n- IEEE Spectrum: `https://spectrum.ieee.org/deepmind-alphaevolve`\n\n---\n\n### 1. Matrix multiplication — 4×4 complex matrices (the headline result)\n\n- **AlphaEvolve multiplies two 4×4 complex-valued matrices using 48 scalar multiplications**, beating the rank-49 obtained by recursively applying **Strassen's 1969 algorithm**. This is \"the **first improvement, after 56 years**, over Strassen's algorithm in this setting.\" (White paper, abstract / §3.1; blog)\n  - Exact white paper quote: *\"...found an algorithm to multiply 4×4 complex-valued matrices using 48 scalar multiplications... offering the first improvement, after 56 years, over Strassen's algorithm in this setting.\"*\n  - The ⟨4,4,4⟩ tensor entry: best known **49** [Strassen ref 95] → AlphaEvolve **48**. (Table 2 / Table 3)\n  - Nuance the paper itself flags (footnote): algorithms using fewer than 49 multiplications existed but did not correspond to valid *tensor decompositions* (i.e., not general exact recursive algorithms). The 48 result uses complex-valued multiplications usable for exact multiplication of complex *or* real matrices.\n  - Source: white paper PDF, abstract + §3.1 + Table 2/3.\n\n- **Broader tensor-decomposition sweep:** Of **54 tensor targets** ⟨m,n,p⟩ (all m,n,p ≤ 5 plus some larger), AlphaEvolve **matched** the state of the art in **38 cases**, **surpassed** it in **14 cases**, and **fell behind** in **2 cases**. (White paper, Table 3 caption)\n  - Example improvements (best known → AlphaEvolve): ⟨3,4,6⟩ 56→54; ⟨3,5,6⟩ 70→68; ⟨2,5,6⟩ 48→47; ⟨4,5,6⟩ 93→90; ⟨2,4,5⟩ 33→32; ⟨4,4,8⟩ 98→96.\n  - Source: white paper PDF, Tables 2 and 3.\n\n### 2. ~50 open math problems — match / improve rates\n\n- AlphaEvolve was applied to **\"a large number (over 50)\"** of open problems in mathematical analysis, geometry, and combinatorics. It **matched the best-known constructions on ~75%** of them, and on **~20%** it **surpassed the SOTA and found new, provably better constructions**. (White paper §1; blog)\n  - White paper quote: *\"...match the best known constructions on ∼75% of them... On ∼20% of the problems, AlphaEvolve surpasses the SOTA and discovers new, provably better constructions.\"*\n  - IEEE Spectrum phrasing: \"for 75 percent of the problems... replicated the already known optimal solution. In 20 percent of cases, it found a new optimum that surpassed any known solution\" (remaining ~5% suboptimal).\n  - Sources: white paper PDF §1; DeepMind blog; IEEE Spectrum.\n\n### 3. Kissing number in 11 dimensions\n\n- AlphaEvolve **improved the lower bound on the 11-dimensional kissing number from 592 to 593**, by finding **593** non-zero 11-dimensional points with integral coordinates whose maximum norm is smaller than their minimum pairwise distance. (White paper §B.11 + §1; blog; IEEE Spectrum)\n  - Exact quote: *\"For d=11, the best known lower bound was 592 [31] and AlphaEvolve improved this to 593.\"*\n  - IEEE Spectrum notes the upper bound remains 868 (gap of 275).\n  - Sources: white paper PDF §B.11; DeepMind blog; IEEE Spectrum.\n\n### 4. Erdős minimum overlap problem\n\n- AlphaEvolve established a **new upper bound** for Erdős's minimum overlap problem (constant C₅). Known bounds were **0.379005 ≤ C₅ ≤ 0.380927** (upper from White, ref 107, via convex programming). AlphaEvolve improved the upper bound to **C₅ ≤ 0.380924** (\"ever so slightly better\"). (White paper §B.5)\n  - Source: white paper PDF §B.5.\n\n### 5. Autocorrelation / uncertainty inequalities (analysis)\n\n- **Uncertainty inequality (constant C₄, Fourier analysis):** known bounds 0.2025 ≤ C₄ ≤ 0.3523. AlphaEvolve improved the upper bound to **C₄ ≤ 0.3521**, and after incorporating a refined approach (suggested by Henry Cohn post-publication) further to **C₄ ≤ 0.3216**. (White paper §B.4)\n- **Autocorrelation inequalities:** AlphaEvolve \"improved the best known bounds on several autocorrelation inequalities\" (paper §3.2 summary lists three; detailed in §B.1–B.3). The blog/§3.2 describes these qualitatively.\n  - Source: white paper PDF §B.4 and §3.2.\n\n### 6. Sums and differences of finite sets (constant C₆)\n\n- For the constant C₆ governing |A−B| vs |A+B|: AlphaEvolve found a set U₁ of size **2003** improving the lower bound to **1.1479 ≤ C₆**, and a larger set U₂ of size **54265** improving it further to **1.1584 ≤ C₆** (upper bound 4/3 ≈ 1.333). (White paper §B.6)\n  - Source: white paper PDF §B.6.\n\n### 7. Other geometry / packing results\n\n- **Packing unit regular hexagons into a regular hexagon:** n=11 best-known outer side **3.943 → 3.931**; n=12 **4.0 → 3.942**. (§B.7)\n- **Min ratio of max-to-min distance:** 2D, 16 points, squared ratio **12.890 → 12.889266112**; 3D, 14 points, **4.168 → 4.165849767**. (§B.8)\n- **Heilbronn problem (triangle), n=11:** SOTA min triangle area **0.036 → >0.0365**. (§B.9)\n- **Heilbronn problem (convex region):** n=13 **0.0306 → 0.0309**; n=14 **0.0277 → 0.0278**. (§B.10)\n  - Source: white paper PDF §§B.7–B.10.\n\n---\n\n**Note on AlphaTensor vs AlphaEvolve confusion (for falsification robustness):** IEEE Spectrum's framing that \"AlphaTensor had already beat the previous best… for multiplying 4×4 matrices\" refers to AlphaTensor's earlier 47-multiplication result over **GF(2)** (mod-2 arithmetic), which is *not* a general algorithm over arbitrary fields. AlphaEvolve's 48 is the first improvement over Strassen's 49 that works as a true tensor decomposition for **complex/real-valued** 4×4 matrices — which is why the paper claims \"56 years.\" Keep these two distinct when checking the claim.\n\n**Most-cited single source for nearly every number above:** the DeepMind white paper PDF (`https://storage.googleapis.com/deepmind-media/DeepMind.com/Blog/alphaevolve-a-gemini-powered-coding-agent-for-designing-advanced-algorithms/AlphaEvolve.pdf`), equivalent to arXiv 2506.13131. The blog post (`https://deepmind.google/discover/blog/alphaevolve-a-gemini-powered-coding-agent-for-designing-advanced-algorithms/`) independently confirms the 48-vs-49 / 56-years claim, the ~50 problems / ~75% / ~20% figures, and the 593 kissing-number configuration."}],"stop_reason":"end_turn","stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":2,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1342,"cache_read_input_tokens":32384,"output_tokens":3076,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":1342},"inference_geo":"not_available","iterations":[{"input_tokens":2,"output_tokens":3076,"cache_read_input_tokens":32384,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1342,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":1342,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"type":"message"}],"speed":"standard"},"diagnostics":null},"requestId":"req_011CcG29U4nj1TwqyoxcHLyu","attributionAgent":"general-purpose","attributionSkill":"deep-research","type":"assistant","uuid":"5fd98719-8b96-4777-80ba-22d66dce54fd","timestamp":"2026-06-21T07:36:32.293Z","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main","slug":"bright-wondering-lantern"}
